<Author>Bubblesdevere
<Content>Barcelona Chic As first time visitors to Barcelona we booked the Emilia on the back of the reviews posted here as they've never let us down yet, and nor did they on this occasion. A taxi from the north coach station cost around 10 Euros. On check in at the hotel we were given lots of useful information about what to see in Barcelona and then went to find our room. Like some of the other guests mentioned earlier we found the heat in the hotel to be unbearable at times which made it difficult to sleep. There is air conditioning but pressing the on/off button and changing the temperature didn't seem to make a difference. We were on the 6th floor and could have opened the full length window, but the room faced out onto a fairly busy street.Our twin room came as two single beds pushed together. Not being used to single beds we found them quite small and what with that and the heat we didn't get a good night's sleep. We decided to have breakfast at the hotel although it was not included in the room rate. It's not cheap at 13 Euros each but the choice was excellent: cheese, salmon, meats, fresh fruit, cereals, yoghurts, various types of gorgeous fresh bread, pastries, eggs, a selection of wonderful preserves, juices - and a glass or two of cava! Things did run out but the staff were very helpful and at no time did we feel there wasn't enough. It was just the perfect way to start a day. A special mention must be made of the selection of teas on offer as they were absolutely delicious and so different from anything I've had before.There is a bar and small restaurant area on the ground floor. Prices for drinks are cheap compared to the UK, around 4 Euros for a glass of decent Rioja.On the first floor mezzanine is what the hotel calls its business area with free internet access and complimentary coffee/tea and pastries between 5 and 7 each evening.The nearest metro station is Rocafort, about 1 minute from the hotel. Playa de Catalunya square is about a 20 minute amble and from here you can visit Las Ramblas or Passieg de Gracia. The Hard Rock cafe Barcelona is in the square and well worth a visit!All in all we were pleased with our choice of hotel: not so far out as to make Barcelona inaccessible but far enough out to be a little quieter. 
