<Author>MikiSMLA
<Content>Not so great Everything good about this hotel is true - clean (the hallway and rooms smell fresh and new), modern furnishings, comfortable bed, great breakfast spread, close to the metro. The stay was going well, until towards the end of the trip where the hotel ran out of water. To be fair, this was not their fault but the city's. However, the way Villa Emilia HANDLED the situation was less to be desired.I noticed the water pressure that night to be low, so I called the reception to ask what the problem was. She sounded incredulous and insisted there was no problem, that perhaps I wasn't flushing properly (which I disputed since we have been there for the past few days and knew how to flush their toilets). When I asked if we can be moved to another room, she said she cannot (which surprised me how she said that so quickly) and had to wait in the morning.As I woke up, there was no water at all. Calling up reception (this time, it was a different person), he quickly reminded me that this was not the hotel's fault but the city's fault and we had to wait for a couple of hours. I've been traveling a lot, both for work and for leisure, and this was the first time I've encountered a situation wherein a service oriented facility offered no... service. At one point, he even asked, What would you like me to do, madam? Call city hall? I replied (regrettably in my head), Yes, and while you're at it, get me a gallon of water to wash my face with. The price of this hotel is not cheap, so if you can afford to stay in chain hotels near the city centre, do so. I believe they can readily and professionally address issues like these instead of small places like Villa Emilia. 
