<Author>JandJTucson
<Content>Barcelona Style We found this hotel on TripAdvisor but booked our stay directly with the hotel. We spent three nights at Emilia before taking a cruise. This is a great little hotel. The rooms, while not large by U.S. standards are beautiful with a very contemporary style. The tile and marble bathroom was one of the most interesting designs I've seen.You absolutely don't want to miss the outdoor, rooftop bar and sitting area. Terrific views of the city and they serve some very nice spanish wines.This hotel is a little farther away from the La Rambla and other tourist sites so it's a bit more quiet but the metro station is just around the corner so you are never more than ten to twenty minutes from most of the must see spots in Barcelona. The metro is inexpensive and very easy to use. We used the metro to get from the Barcelona airport to the hotel. The connections were easy but be aware, their are stairs to negotiate with your bags are many of the metro stations.The staff at Emilia was very friendly and helpful with the exception on one fellow at the front desk. We only saw him one time during our stay.The lobby bar and small restaurant is very contemporary and stylish but it comes with a price. It's very expensive. There's a great little bakery/pastry shop just a few doors away for coffee and pastry as well as lunch items. If you are interested in the hotel, you might watch the specials link on their website. We were lucky enough to book a package that included the buffet breakfast which was very good. The items are typical of a European breakfast so don't expect to find scarmbled eggs and hashbrowns.In a city with a lot of hotels, I think this one is a great find. It's only been open a couple of years so some of the travel guides don't list it.Finally, we found a great, reasonably priced restaurant just about three blocks away on the Grand Via. It's called La Clara and has a great tapas bar on the street level and a very nice, full menu restaurant in the underground wine cellar. 
